Lab: Probability Distribution

    Estimated reading time: 30 minutes

    In this lab, you will learn how to use the concept of probability distribution in a real-life scenario using Microsoft Excel.

    Software used in this lab

    The instructional videos in this course use the full Microsoft Excel Desktop version as this has all the available product features, but for the hands-on labs, we will be using the free "Excel for the web" version as this is available to everyone.

    Although you can use the Excel Desktop software, it is recommended that you use Excel for the web for the hands-on labs, as the lab instructions specifically refer to this version, and there are some minor differences in the interface and available features.

    Data set

    This data set has been created manually.

    Learning objectives:

    • Calculate the average return and risk based on estimated probability distributions.
    • Simulate a continuous probability distribution by sampling values from a discrete distribution to find the average return.

    Welcome to the Lab: Probability distribution!

    Exercise 1: Estimate the average return and the standard deviation based on the given probability distribution

    A stock market investor, Ryan, is concerned about the market returns for the upcoming year. The market return is calculated as a percentage gain over the investment during the year.

    Ryan identifies five possible economic outcomes for the country in the coming year: rapid expansion, moderate expansion, no growth, moderate contraction, and serious contraction. He uses the information available to him to assess the probabilities of these economic outcomes and estimate the stock market returns for each case.

    Use the provided information to estimate the average stock market return expected and the risk associated with this estimate.

    The estimated probabilities and returns are provided in the following worksheet: M3L1_Lab_Probability_Distribution_Market Return.xlsx. To download the file, right-click and open the link in a new tab. Then, open the file in Excel for the web to follow the steps given in this lab.

    1. Calculate the average return
      Use the formula: =SUMPRODUCT(array1, [array2], [array3], …)

      In this case, you will calculate the sum product of the probability of the outcome and the estimated return for each outcome, as shown below. You will get an average return is 0.153 or 15.3%.

    2. Calculate the square deviations from the mean
      To calculate the overall variance, first calculate the square deviations from the mean. This involves squaring the difference between each individual return and the average return.

    3. Calculate the variance
      Next, calculate the variance. The variance is the sum product of the probability and the square deviations. It will be calculated as shown below. The variance calculated is 0.002811.

    4. Calculate the standard deviation
      Lastly, calculate the standard deviation. The standard deviation is the square root of the variance. Use the SQRT function to calculate the square root. The answer is 5.3%.

    Exercise 2: Simulate a continuous probability distribution by sampling values from a discrete distribution to find the average return

    This exercise illustrates how to sample values from a discrete distribution to simulate a continuous probability distribution. Simulate enough economic outcomes and then find the average and standard deviation of the probable return.

    To simulate a continuous probability distribution:

    • Generate a large number of random probabilities (values from 0 to 1).
    • Assign the probable return for each probability based on the estimated values (The estimated stock market return for various economic outcomes and the probability of such outcomes).
    • Calculate the mean and standard deviation for the simulated market returns and compare them with the mean and standard deviation originally calculated.

    Let's begin. In the Simulation worksheet, populate the average return and standard deviation values calculated in Exercise 1 to help you compare the corresponding values that will be calculated in Exercise 2.

    The simulated data set will comprise 400 probabilities randomly generated, and the corresponding market returns based on the research-based estimates provided. Follow the steps to generate the simulated data set.

    1. Generate 400 random probability values by typing RAND() in the cell. The RAND() function randomly generates a number between 0 and 1.

    2. Next, calculate the simulated market return for each random probability using cumulative probabilities. Cumulative probabilities allow us to determine ranges of probability values to which the market return can be assigned. The table below explains the concept.

    Economic outcome Probability of the outcome Cumulative probabilities Estimated stock market return
    Rapid Expansion 0.12 0.00 23%
    Moderate Expansion 0.40 0.12 (0.00 + 0.12) 18%
    No Growth 0.25 0.52 (0.12 + 0.40) 15%
    Moderate Contraction 0.15 0.77 (0.52 + 0.25) 9%
    Serious Contraction 0.08 0.92 (0.77 + 0.15) 3%

    This means that the probability values from 0.00 to 0.12 will be assigned a market return of 23%, probability values from 0.12 to 0.52 will be assigned a market return of 18%, and so on. The probability values from 0.92 to 1 will be assigned a market return of 3%. The market returns will be assigned using the VLOOKUP function. To run VLOOKUP, we need the cumulative probabilities and the market return. Therefore, create the Lookup Table as shown below.

    1. Using VLOOKUP, assign market returns to each of the probabilities. Let's examine the VLOOKUP function.

      =VLOOKUP(lookup_value, table_array, col_index_num, [range_lookup])

      lookup_value: The value you want to look up. In this case, it is the random probability value to which you need to assign the market return.

      table_array: The range where the lookup value needs to be searched. Ideally, the first column should have the lookup value. Other columns will have the values that need to be returned. In this case, the first column needs to be the cumulative probabilities, and the second column will be the market return.

      col_index_num: The column number that has the value that needs to be returned. In this case, it is the second column.

      [range_lookup]: Optionally, you may enter 'TRUE' if you want an approximate match and 'FALSE' if you want an exact match. If no value is entered, the default value is 'TRUE'. In this case, we need an approximate match. Therefore, we can skip entering a value as it will assume the default, 'TRUE'.

    1. Now that the simulated data set has been created, let's calculate the mean and standard deviation of the market return.

      To calculate the mean, use the AVERAGE function. In this case, the mean is 15.5%, which is close to the average return calculated earlier.

    To calculate the standard deviation, use the STDEV.S function. The standard deviation is 5.3%, which is very close to the standard deviation calculated earlier.

    Congratulations! You've completed the lab activity on probability distribution, and you are ready to move to the next topic.
